The defendant Rianna Y. Barrett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation is revoked and a prison term is not ordered, or if probation is discharged or terminated, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of any restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.

Must continue to attend high school and must successfully graduate.  Must seek and maintain employment during summer months and when not in school.  That employment must be satisfactory to probation agent.  Must not leave or change employment without prior approval of probation agent.

Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, the bar areas of restaurants. Defendant may not possess or consume any alcohol, nor be anywhere alcohol is available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located.  No contact with victim in this case unless your probation agent approves.
Defendant may apply for expungement if probation successfully completed and all court obligations are satisfied.

The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  If agent deems appropriate you must participate in the JCI Reality Program or a similar program in Minnesota.  Must comply with any other recommendations of your probation agent.  A restitution hearing will be held at a later date to determine if there will be restitution ordered.
Restitution hearing held February 3, 2015.  Restitution is set at $0.00.
